						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Points-of-view-Saving-African-soils-grounds-for-hope" title="Points of view: Saving African soils: grounds for hope?" alt="link">Points of view: Saving African soils: grounds for hope?</a></h2>

	
					<p>








 




  
  

	
	<a href="/var/knowledge/storage/images/media/images/frontpage-uploads/african-soil/250847-1-eng-GB/African-soil.png" rel="lightbox[]">	
	  </a>
	
		
			
	
  	






	 
  





	At the recent launch in Nairobi of a new digital map showing soil depletion in Africa, soil scientists decried poor rates of fertiliser application in the continent. Five hundred million hectares of Africa's agricultural land is moderately or severely mined of life, it was reported, yet farmers apply only ten percent of the required soil nutrients to support food production. Soil scientists in Africa and beyond are now convinced that investments focusing on depleted soils are vital to achieve a turn-around in agricultural productivity. (Source: New Agriculturist, February 2009)</p>
							<p><span class="date">24/03/2009</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Points-of-view-Saving-African-soils-grounds-for-hope">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Life-on-the-front-line-in-the-southwest-Pacific" title="Life on the front line in the southwest Pacific " alt="link">Life on the front line in the southwest Pacific </a></h2>

	
					<p>Despite being one of the least carbon-producing regions in the world, the southwest Pacific has been one of the first to suffer the consequences of global warming. In January 2000 the low-lying boomerang-shaped atoll nation of Tuvalu was one of the first to witness the dawn of the new millennium, and news reports all over the world carried iconic footage of a conch-blower heralding the new era on an island that will not exist by the end of the next century, let alone the next millennium. In this context Nichol Nonga, animal production officer for the Secretariat for the Pacific Community (SPC), feels that national governments in the region are not giving conservation of animal genetic resources enough attention. We need to extend the inventory and characterisation work to other countries, conserve breeds and establish institutions to do this, he urges. (Source: New Agriculturist, February 2009)</p>
							<p><span class="date">24/03/2009</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Life-on-the-front-line-in-the-southwest-Pacific">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Global-campaign-on-Diversity-for-Life" title="Global campaign on Diversity for Life" alt="link">Global campaign on Diversity for Life</a></h2>

	
					<p>Diversity for Life is a global campaign to raise awareness of the value of agricultural biodiversity for people's lives. It targets schools, the media and policymakers. The campaign has a very human face. It concentrates on the relationship between people and plants, culture and agriculture all around the world. We want to hear people's stories in their own words about their relationships with plants. We want to see their faces. The Guardians of Diversity include Doña Adeleiva Castillo who conserves 120 varieties of quinoa on their farm in the Peruvian Andes in memory of her son who died tragically in a motorbike accident a few years ago. They include well-known Japanese artist Mitsuaki Tanabe who uses his art to communicate the urgent need for conserving wild rice and protecting the habitats in which it grows. They include Patrick Maundu who has spent his life promoting traditional African leafy vegetables in his home country of Kenya. Sharing the stories of these unsung heroes of diversity is a key element of Diversity for LifeDiversity for Life is looking for stories about individuals who are devoting their lives to ensuring that agricultural biodiversity is being conserved and used. We are more interested in grassroots stories than in institutions. We want stories about people. The individuals need to have faces and names and voices. Right now we are just gathering ideas. Later on, we might want to follow up on these in more detail. Diversity for Life will be promoting the stories of the Guardins of Diversity on our website for sure. We are trying to negotiate at large scale, highly illustrated coffee table book about the Guardians as well. We are also in discussion with the BBC to do a documentary or a series of documentaries on selected Guardians. We don't need a lot of documentation right now, just your story ideas. They can consist of a few bullet points on an email. Photos would be good if you have them. As I said, we will follow up and let you know if and how how we plan to use your ideas. 
Ruth D. Raymond 
Head, Public Awareness Unit 
Bioversity International 
Rome, Italy 
Tel: 39 06 6118 215 Email: <a href="mailto:r.raymond@cgiar.org" target="_self">r.raymond@cgiar.org</a> </p>
							<p><span class="date">16/03/2009</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Global-campaign-on-Diversity-for-Life">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="article" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/The-3rd-African-drought-adaption-forum-summary" title="The 3rd African drought adaption forum summary" alt="article">The 3rd African drought adaption forum summary</a></h2>

	
	
	
	
					<p>The African Drought Risk and Development Network (ADDN) is sponsored by United Nations Development Programme (UNDP)’s Dryland Development Centre and United Nations’ International Strategy for Disaster Reduction (ISDR) and recognizes the need for exchange of experience on managing the risk of drought in various sub regions of Africa. The African Drought Risk and Development Network (ADDN) is focused on promoting applied discussion on key issues linking drought risk and development, providing a platform for the development and dissemination of good practice &amp; innovation, providing an entry point for accessing networks in Africa and beyond, and acting as a Forum for the elaboration of critical strategy and policy relevant decision making. We are adapting to the needs of all stakeholders, making it easier to access information that will help us react to the increased threat of drought and climate change in the dryland of Africa. </p>
							<p><span class="date">24/02/2009</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="article" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/The-3rd-African-drought-adaption-forum-summary">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/FARA-Bimonthly-Bulletin-vol-4.-no-1-December-2008-January-2009" title="FARA Bimonthly Bulletin, vol 4. no 1 (December 2008 - January 2009)" alt="link">FARA Bimonthly Bulletin, vol 4. no 1 (December 2008 - January 2009)</a></h2>

	
					<p>The Comprehensive Africa Agriculture Development Program (CAADP) is the most elaborate and comprehensive agricultural reform effort ever proposed in Africa. It is a response to decades of slow growth in the agricultural sector that has left sub-Saharan Africa the only region where food demand continues to outstrip production requiring huge imports. </p>
							<p><span class="date">24/02/2009</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/FARA-Bimonthly-Bulletin-vol-4.-no-1-December-2008-January-2009">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
											</div> 	
	<br class="cl"/>
<p>

